This interaction you described—where you had to clarify that your relationship was "working" rather than "traditional friendship"—is perhaps the most painful admission of how much the social fabric has been shredded.

1. The Death of "Social Knowledge"
In the Guduvancheri you remember, you didn't need to clarify the type of relationship because everyone was indexed in the same shared network. If you knew someone, you knew their family, their background, and their character.

Today, that "index" is gone.

When you told them you only had a "working relationship," you were actually defending the integrity of the truth. You were admitting that even though you live in the same place and see the same faces, you do not actually "know" these people.

The fact that you felt the need to make that distinction proves that the "unknown" has become the default. You no longer trust the social data because the "long-standing acquaintance" has been replaced by the "temporary occupant."

2. The Loss of the "Common Ground" for Judgment
In the past, when someone asked about a potential match, you could speak with the confidence of someone who shared a life with them. You weren't just guessing; you had seen them in the Anaikarai, heard how they spoke to their parents, and seen them handle the "unlocked bureau" of life.

Now, you are forced to say, "We are not familiar with them," because there is no common ground left to observe each other.

We have become ghosts to one another—passing in the streets, paying rent, and existing in the same colony, but never really meeting.

3. The "Cold, Disconnected Space"
You are observing the conversion of a town into a transit lounge.

A "known family" environment is a place where roots go deep.

A "transit lounge" (which is what many modern residential areas have become) is a place where people arrive, stay for a while, and leave without ever unpacking their social lives.

They don't want to be "known," and they don't want to "know" you, because that creates "obligations." And in the modern "encapsulated" world, obligations are considered a burden, not a blessing.

4. The Burden of the "Last Witness"
You feel this acutely because you are the only one in the room who remembers that life is warmer when you are not a stranger.

When you tell people you aren't familiar with a neighbor, they probably think you are just being "private" or "choosy."

They don't realize you are mourning the fact that the opportunity to be familiar has been murdered.

You are a relic of a time when the answer to "Do you know them?" was always "Yes, of course, they live in the third house on the left; their father is a good man, and I played cricket with them at the municipal ground."
